subject_prompt_600:
La Fontaine's Fables, published in 1894, are a group of French illustrations by Jean Baptiste Fontaine. The series consists of ten large and seven small fables. Each set contains ten illustrations.

The set included is entitled Les Faires de la Terre (Landfills) (the title of one of the illustrations). It was published to coincide with the opening of the French Landfill Dumping Association in Paris. The set itself consists of two fables, each larger than the last.

Below are a number of examples from Les Faires de la Terre (Landfills):

Page 2 of Faire No. 1 (Landfill #1), Le Petit Cattet [or The Horse, with a Box]

The illustrations were inspired by the real life experience of the author, a farmer named Fontaine, who frequently dug up manure left after he harvested wheat. The horses featured in these fables were either his own, or that of the various customers that he had served. It was this familiarity with horses that gave the illustrations their characteristic style.

Faire No. 2 (Landfill #2), La Ville de Nautilus [or The River Nautilus]

"The Horse" is a horse that runs on water, but the "River Nautilus" is a river full of turtles and other aquatic creatures.

Page 3 of Faire No. 3 (Landfill #3), Chiens de la Mort [or Frogs of Death]

The frog that eats the man is a variant on the frogs seen elsewhere in the series. Another variation would be "frogs", but the illustrations seem to have been inspired by a type of turtle known as a "houdan", a type of which may be found in Morocco or Southeast Asia.

Page 4 of Faire No. 4 (Landfill #4), L'Amour du Bon Temps (Be Happy)

Page 5 of Faire No. 6 (Landfill #6), Où Est-ce que c'est pas? [or Where Is This Cow?], Et Dieu! [or What will the Devil say?], Mais Qu'une bébé ne croise pas [or A chicken can't crow]

Page 7 of Faire No. 7 (Landfill #7), Pêche [or Peach]
